Heparin induced thrombocytopaenia

Arises because heparin stimulates HIT antibody production.
Antibodies bind to PF4 on the platelet surface and stimulate platelet activation.

This results in thrombocytopaenia (platelets found to to antibodies are removed by the Reticuloendothelial system) - commonest manifestation.
Associated thrombosis (venous more than arterial) - around 50%, if untreated. Manifestations include pulmonary embolism, skin necrosis, limb gangrene. Arterial thrombi (MI, stroke) can also occur.

Bleeding is rare.

Onset is 5 - 10 days after onset of therapy.
Risk Heparin > fractionated heparin
High dose > low dose

"4 T" score is used to assess the likelihood of HIT.
Treatment: Stop heparin and start non heparin anti-coagulation

Thrombophilias

![heritable thrombophilias.png](heritable thrombophilias.png)

The following are heritable thrombophilias

  • Factor V Leiden - gain of coagulant function
  • Protein C deficiency - loss of anticoagulant function
  • protein S deficiency - loss of anticoagulant function
  • Antithrombin deficiency

Heritable thrombophilias mostly cause venous thrombosis. (except for )

The main acquired thrombophilias are

  • Antiphospholipid syndrome
  • [[Coagulation#Heparin induced thrombocytopaenia|HIT]]

The need for thrombophilia testing is controversial because

  • Identification of heritable thrombophilia does not influence acute management of VTE

  • nor does it alter the risk of recurrent VTE.

  • heritable thrombophilias are seen in 20% of bases of VTE

  • not associated with arterial thrombosis.

Thrombophilias can be

  • gain of function of procoagulant defects.
    • Factor V Leiden - a mutated version of factor V which leads to Factor Va which is resistant to inactivation by protein C.
  • loss of function of anticoagulants
    • Antithrombin deficiency

Factor 5 Leiden

A mutated version of factor V which leads to Factor Va which is resistant to inactivation by protein C.
5% prevalence in Europeans
Associated with fivefold risk of VTE. Synergistic risk with OCP and pregnancy.
-- but overall still very low absolute risk.

Some prothrombin mutations

Antithrombin deficiency

Increased risk of VTE.
Caused by loss of function mutation of antithrombin
Diagnosed by measuring antithrombin levels.
Defects are genetically too diverse for genetic testing to be clinically viable.
Spuriously low antithrombin levels are caused by:

  • heparin therapy
  • Nephrotic syndrome
  • Liver disease
  • Acute inflammation
  • post surgical

Protein C and protein S deficiency

Both are vitamin K dependent anti-clotting factors. They inactivate factor Va and factor VIIIa.
Many mutations can cause reduced function; therefore for diagnosis, assays measure protein concentration.
Spuriously low Protein C and S values can be seen in

  • vitamin K deficiency / Warfarin use
  • Acute illness
  • Liver disease
  • Protein S levels are lowered in pregnancy

Heterozygous inheritance of protein C and S causes mild hypercoagulable state. Rare homozygous inheritance causes neonatal purpura fulminans.

Antiphospholipid syndrome - APS

Acquired thrombophilia
Increased risk of recurrent VTE

[!TIP] Suspect APS if there is venous thrombosis at unsual site or unusual time (age<50)

[!INFO] Definition: VTE / arterial thrombosis and/or recurrent pregnancy loss with persistently elevated aPL antibodies => APS
i.e aPL +ve with at least one relevant symptom.

Suspect if:

  • VTE at age < 50
  • recurrent VTE while on thromboprophylaxis
  • VTE at unusual sites
  • Unexplained arterial thrombosis < 50 years
  • Recurrent foetal loss < 10 weeks POA or other unexplained foetal loss
  • prolonged APTT found on routine tests (==Why is APTT prolonged in the thrombophilia?==)

DVT

Pathophysiology of DVT

Thrombosis = intravascular formation of a clot as opposed to haemostatic clot formation outside vessels.

Arterial Vs. Venous thrombosis

Arterial thrombosis -
Characterized by

  1. high sheer stress environment
  2. exposure of subendothelial tissue following plaque rupture
    Resulting in white thrombi - composed of platelets and fibrin.
    Main factors : turbulence and vessel wall dysfunction

Venous thrombosis -
Low sheer stress environment.
Therefore, red thrombi -> rich in red cells and fibrin.
main factors: Stasis and hypercoagulability.

DVT terminology

Distal - confined to calf veins
Proximal - extending into popliteal vein; larger and more like to embolize

Unusual site DVT: not originating in the deep veins of the leg.

[!INFO] ECG in pulmonary emblism
#ECG - Right ventricular strain pattern = T inversion in II,III,aVF and right chest leads V1-V4.

VTE risk factors


What is provoked and unproved DVT

DVT can be due to a transient risk factor or Long term risk factors ("predisposing factors" ).

Unprovoked DVT => VTE where no identifiable provoking event or risk factor is evident

Provoked DVT => VTE caused by a known event or risk factor (eg, surgery, hospital admission, estrogen)

Underlying diseases which cause DVT

Management of DVT

3 phases: Acute phase, maintenance phase and long term phase.

Acute phase

[!WARNING] Warfarin and DOACs cross the placenta
SHOULD NOT BE USED IN #pregnancy
DOC in pregnancy is LMWH = enoxa
If pregnant patient is already on warfarin, change to enoxa by the 6th week, when warfarin has high risk of causing embryopathy.

Traditional management:
  1. Parenteral anticoagulant + warfarin- provides immediate anticoagulation
    1. heparin or enoxaparin or fondaparinux + warfarin.

Parenteral therapy stopped once INR >= 2.0

Use of direct oral anticoagulants - newer regimens for acute treatment

Edoxaban and dabigatran - preceded by parenteral therapy for 5 days followed by a switch to DOAC.
Apixaban and rivaroxaban - no parenteral therapy required. But given for a higher dose for 7 to 21 days respectively.

Basis of pharmacotherapy

Anticoagulants prevent clot extension but do no dissolve formed clots.
but Thrombolytic drugs are not used in VTE because of their high bleeding risk. -> Can be given in life threatening situation.

Duration etc

3 months

Stopping anticoagulation before 3 months duration -> higher risk of recurrence. (5% within the next year)

Continuing treatment beyond 3 months doesn't have added benefit.

When to extend more than 3 months

Risk of recurrence Vs. Bleeding is compared to decide whether to extend duration.
High risk > 5% over 1 year.
Intermediate > 3%
Low 1-3%

Few examples as rules of thumb:

  1. More than one episode of unprovoked proximal DVT or symptomatic PE -> indefiinite anticoagulation
  2. For most patients with a first episode of unprovoked proximal DVT and/or symptomatic PE -> indefinite anticoagulation.
  3. Patients with active cancer -> may indefinite anticoagulation (compare with risk of bleeding)

Haemostasis


How to read this diagram:

  1. The quickest response to endothelial damange is formation of the platelet plug. Platelets roll off the exposed collagen and stick to it.
    1. The platelets bind to collagen - adhesion
    2. secrete their granules - activation
    3. bind to each other - aggregation
  2. Platelets form the primary haemostatic plug within about 1 minute. This needs to be stabilized by the coagulation cascade proteins.

Formation of the primary platelet plug

ALS

Commonest Type of of Motor neurone disease
Quickly and relentlessly progressing: death in about 5 years<- neuromuscular respiratory failure
Hallmark is mixture of upper and lower motor neurons signs
Ataxia is not a feature
Extra pyramidal features can mimic Parkinson's - tremor, bradykinesia; may precede or follow motor signs.

UMN <- degeneration of frontal lobe motor neurons and the corticospinal tract.

No objective sensory losses.

Non motor symptoms:

  • Labile mood - "pseudobulbar effect" - unstoppable laughing or crying; common
  • cognitive impairment <- frontotemporal dysfunction

There is data to support the role for anti coagulants or anti-platelet medications to reduce the risk of thromboembolization in IE.
